Step 2: Design and Test a Model Architecture¶

Question 1¶

Describe the techniques used to preprocess the data.

Answer¶

I used two main pro-processing steps:

  1. Normalizing the images so that they pixel values are between -0.5 and 0.5
  2. Equalizing all the 3 channels so that the brightness effect is removed

I also introduced transformation of existing training data set to allow generation of additional training images. The transformation consisted of rotation, translation and shear as seen below. The maximum rotation angle is limited to 20 degrees because larger rotation angles might result in some signs looking similar and confusing the training algorithm. The shear and translation are limited to 5 pixels.

In [33]:
### Preprocess the data here. It is required to normalize the data. Other preprocessing steps could include 
### converting to grayscale, etc.
### Feel free to use as many code cells as needed.

def normalize_image(image):
    image = image/255-0.5
    return image

def equalize_channels(image):
    image[:,:,0] = cv2.equalizeHist(image[:,:,0])
    image[:,:,1] = cv2.equalizeHist(image[:,:,1])
    image[:,:,2] = cv2.equalizeHist(image[:,:,2])
    return image

def grayscale_image(image):
    gray_image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    return gray_image

def equalize_grayscale(image):
    image = cv2.equalizeHist(image)
    return image

def transform_image(image,angle,shear,trans):
    
    #rotation
    rotation_angle = np.random.uniform(angle)-angle/2
    rows,cols,ch = image.shape    
    rotation_matrix = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((cols/2,rows/2),rotation_angle,1)
    image = cv2.warpAffine(image,rotation_matrix,(cols,rows))

    # Translation
    deltaX = trans*np.random.uniform()-trans/2
    deltaY = trans*np.random.uniform()-trans/2
    trans_matrix = np.float32([[1,0,deltaX],[0,1,deltaY]])
    image = cv2.warpAffine(image,trans_matrix,(cols,rows))

    # Shear
    pts1 = np.float32([[10,10],[20,10],[10,20]])
    pt1 = 10+shear*np.random.uniform()-shear/2
    pt2 = 20+shear*np.random.uniform()-shear/2
    pts2 = np.float32([[pt1,10],[pt2,pt1],[10,pt2]])

    shear_matrix = cv2.getAffineTransform(pts1,pts2)
        
    image = cv2.warpAffine(image,shear_matrix,(cols,rows))
    
    return image

def generate_data(X_train,y_train,angle,shear,trans):
    n_train = len(y_train)
    
    X_new = []
    y_new = []
    for i in range(n_train):
        
        for j in range(5):
            trans_image = transform_image(X_train[i],angle,shear,trans)
            X_new.append(trans_image)
            y_new.append(y_train[i])
            
    X_new = np.array(X_new)
    y_new = np.array(y_new)
    
    return X_new, y_new

def show(image):
    plt.figure(figsize = (3,3))
    plt.imshow(image)

def plot_transformed(row,col,X,y):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(row,col, figsize=(12, 12))
    fig.subplots_adjust(hspace = .2, wspace=.001)

        axs[i+1].set_title(y_train[index])
    plt.show()

Question 2¶

Describe how you set up the training, validation and testing data for your model. If you generated additional data, why?

Answer:¶

The data was already split into training, validation, and testing sets, so I didn't have to do the splitting. However since the training data was limited, I generated additional data using the transformation described earlier. 5 additional images were generated for each of the training image with random transformation parameters with constant means.

Question 3¶

What does your final architecture look like? (Type of model, layers, sizes, connectivity, etc.) For reference on how to build a deep neural network using TensorFlow, see Deep Neural Network in TensorFlow from the classroom.

Answer:¶

The structure used is described below

Layer 1¶
  • Convolution 1x1 filter output shape is same as input shape 32x32x3
  • Convolution 5x5 filter with 16 outputs
  • Convolution 5x5 filter with 32 outputs
  • 2x2 max pooling

This layer is repeated 2 more times with increasing number of outputs. The 1x1 convolution layers are used to increase the depth without significantly increasing the comuptational costs.

The output of the last layer is flattened for connection to a fully connected layer. It is possible to have many different architectures and add complexity through inception modules and so on. But here I just chose this architecture once the validation accuracy exceeded 98%.

The two fully connected layers have 50% drop outs layer after each to prevent over fitting. This is finally connectd to the output layer with 43 outputs for the 43 classes.

The test accuracy reached was 96.8%.

In [41]:
from tensorflow.contrib.layers import flatten

def LeNet(x,keep_prob):

    # Arguments used for tf.truncated_normal, randomly defines variables for the weights and biases for each layer
    mu = 0
    sigma = 0.1

    conv_strides = [1, 1, 1, 1]
    pool_strides = [1, 2, 2, 1]

    weights = {
        'wc0': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(1, 1, 3, 3), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc1': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 3, 16), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc2': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 16, 32), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc3': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(1, 1, 32, 32), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc4': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 32, 64), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc5': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 64, 128), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc6': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(1, 1, 128, 128), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc7': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 128, 256), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wc8': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(5, 5, 256, 256), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wd1': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(4096, 1024), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'wd2': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(1024, 256), mean = mu, stddev = sigma)),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal(shape=(256, n_classes), mean = mu, stddev = sigma))}

    biases = {
        'bc0': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(3)),
        'bc1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(16)),
        'bc2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(32)),
        'bc3': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(32)),
        'bc4': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(64)),
        'bc5': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(128)),
        'bc6': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(128)),
        'bc7': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(256)),
        'bc8': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(256)),
        'bd1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(1024)),
        'bd2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(256)),
        'out': tf.Variable(tf.zeros(n_classes))}

    # Layer 0: input 32, 32, 3 output 32, 32, 3
    conv0 = tf.nn.conv2d(x, weights['wc0'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv0 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv0, biases['bc0'])
    conv0 = tf.nn.relu(conv0)
    print('Conv0',conv0.get_shape())

    # Layer 1: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv1 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv0, weights['wc1'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv1 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv1, biases['bc1'])
    conv1 = tf.nn.relu(conv1)
    print('Conv1',conv1.get_shape())

    # Layer 2: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv2 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv1, weights['wc2'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv2 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv2, biases['bc2'])
    conv2 = tf.nn.relu(conv2)
    print('Conv2',conv2.get_shape())

    # Pooling
    conv2 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv2, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=pool_strides, padding='SAME')
    print('Pool Conv2',conv2.get_shape())

    # Layer 3: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv3 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv2, weights['wc3'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv3 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv3, biases['bc3'])
    conv3 = tf.nn.relu(conv3)
    print('Conv2',conv3.get_shape())

    # Layer 4: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv4 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv3, weights['wc4'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv4 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv4, biases['bc4'])
    conv4 = tf.nn.relu(conv4)
    print('Conv4',conv4.get_shape())

    # Layer 5: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv5 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv4, weights['wc5'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv5 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv5, biases['bc5'])
    conv5 = tf.nn.relu(conv5)
    print('Conv5',conv5.get_shape())

    # Pooling
    conv5 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv5, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=pool_strides, padding='SAME')
    print('Pool Conv5',conv5.get_shape())

    # Layer 6: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv6 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv5, weights['wc6'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv6 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv6, biases['bc6'])
    conv6 = tf.nn.relu(conv6)
    print('Conv6',conv6.get_shape())

    # Layer 7: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv7 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv6, weights['wc7'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv7 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv7, biases['bc7'])
    conv7 = tf.nn.relu(conv7)
    print('Conv7',conv7.get_shape())

    # Layer 8: Convolutional. Input = . Output = 
    conv8 = tf.nn.conv2d(conv7, weights['wc8'], strides=conv_strides, padding='SAME')
    conv8 = tf.nn.bias_add(conv8, biases['bc8'])
    conv8 = tf.nn.relu(conv8)
    print('Conv8',conv8.get_shape())

    # Pooling
    conv8 = tf.nn.max_pool(conv8, ksize=[1, 2, 2, 1], strides=pool_strides, padding='SAME')
    print('Pool Conv8',conv8.get_shape())

    # concatenate layers after dropping
    flatten_conv2 = flatten(conv2)
    flatten_conv5 = flatten(conv5)
    flatten_conv8 = flatten(conv8)
    print('Flat8', flatten_conv8.get_shape())

    # Layer Fully Connected. Using only the last flat layer
    fc1 = tf.add(tf.matmul(flatten_conv8, weights['wd1']),biases['bd1'])
    fc1 = tf.nn.relu(fc1)
    fc1 = tf.nn.dropout(fc1, keep_prob)
    print('fc1',fc1.get_shape())

    # Layer Fully Connected.
    fc2 = tf.add(tf.matmul(fc1, weights['wd2']),biases['bd2'])
    fc2 = tf.nn.relu(fc2)
    fc2 = tf.nn.dropout(fc2, keep_prob)
    print('fc2',fc2.get_shape())

    # Layer Fully Connected. 
    logits = tf.add(tf.matmul(fc2, weights['out']),biases['out'])
    print('logits',logits.get_shape())
    
    labels_pred = tf.nn.softmax(logits)
    
    regularizer = (tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc0']) 
                    + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc1']) + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc2']) 
                    + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc3']) + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc4']) 
                    + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc5']) + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc6']) 
                    + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc7']) + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wc8']) 
                    + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wd1']) + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['wd2'])
                    + tf.nn.l2_loss(weights['out']))
    
    return logits, regularizer, labels_pred
In [42]:
rate = 0.001

logits, regulizer, labels_pred = LeNet(x, keep_prob)
cross_entropy = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(labels=one_hot_y, logits=logits)
loss_operation = tf.reduce_mean(cross_entropy)+1e-6*regulizer
optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate = rate)
training_operation = optimizer.minimize(loss_operation)

correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(logits, 1), tf.argmax(one_hot_y, 1))
accuracy_operation = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, tf.float32))
saver = tf.train.Saver()

def evaluate(X_data, y_data):
    num_examples = len(X_data)
    total_accuracy = 0
    sess = tf.get_default_session()
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
        batch_x, batch_y = X_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE], y_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE]
        accuracy = sess.run(accuracy_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob: 1.0})
        total_accuracy += (accuracy * len(batch_x))
    return total_accuracy / num_examples

with tf.Session() as sess:
    sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())
    num_examples = len(processed_X_train)
    
    print("Training...")
    print()
    for i in range(EPOCHS):

            batch_x, batch_y = pro_X_train[offset:end], pro_y_train[offset:end]
            sess.run(training_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob: 0.5})
            
        validation_accuracy = evaluate(processed_X_valid, processed_y_valid)
        print("EPOCH {} ...".format(i+1))
        print("Validation Accuracy = {:.3f}".format(validation_accuracy))
        print()
        
        saver.save(sess, './my_tsnet.ckpt')
            
    print("Model saved")

Question 5¶

Solution approach?

Answer¶

I started with the Lenet architecture with gave me 80% validation accuracy at the outset without any modification to the images. Preprocessing the images improved the accuracy to about 92%. After this I started tweaking the hyper parameters to see if I can gain any improvement. This was the most inefficient part of the process - essetially tuning some parameters to gain some improvement in performance. Soon I abondoned this and started focusing on the network architecture. Literature suggested having 3 layers to identify features from basic shapes like lines to more advanced features. The lectures also suggested using 1x1 filter convolutions to increase depth without incurring computational penalties. This was used to come up with the architecture described above.

There are a lot of knobs to turn here to gain small improvements here and there, but once I got the validation accuracy above 98% I stopped fiddling with the structure and the hyper parameters.

def read_images(filename):
    img = cv2.imread(filename)
    img = cv2.resize(img,(32,32))
    return img

def transform_german_images(filename):
    img = cv2.imread(filename)
    img = cv2.resize(img,(32,32))
    
    img[:,:,0] = cv2.equalizeHist(img[:,:,0])
    img[:,:,2] = cv2.equalizeHist(img[:,:,2])
    img[:,:,1] = cv2.equalizeHist(img[:,:,1])
    img = img/255.-.5
    
    return img

        axs[i].imshow(image)

Predict the Sign Type for Each Image¶

Question 6¶

Choose five candidate images of traffic signs and provide them in the report. Are there any particular qualities of the image(s) that might make classification difficult?

Answer:¶

Random images were downloaded from the German data set. The netwrok will perform well on images which it has obviously seen before, however, images which are completely new will most likely be misclassified. It is also possible that color might confuse the network. For example in the US data set, Stop sign has a large area with red color. If a sign with large red area is observed, in absence of strong distinguishing features, it might be misclassified.

Analyze Performance¶

The performance on the new images is compared to the accuracy results of the test set is poor 79% vs 96.8%.

79% is also a pretty high value. I wuld have expected it to be even lower. It is possible that the images I chose were coincedentally similar to US data set. The network has most trouble with the speed limit signs and signs with large red areas.
